Q: How can I iterate a flat_map in a range-based &#39;for&#39; loop, updating values? A: <p><code>auto &amp;&amp;</code> will <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13230480/what-is-the-meaning-of-a-variable-with-type-auto">match the const/volatile/ref state of each variable</a>.</p>
<pre><code>for (auto &amp;&amp;[k, v] : m) {
    v++;
}
</code></pre>
<p><a href="https://godbolt.org/z/E5KMYaPjb" rel="nofollow noreferrer">See it working</a></p>

Q: How to Update Grid Item going from top to bottom in 2D Array in C++ A: <p>If you want to go from top to bottom, you need to iterate the rows with a loop.</p>
<p>First, in order to be more generic, let's define constants for the number of rows and the number of columns:</p>
<pre><code>constexpr int NROWS = 12;
constexpr int NCOLS = 8;
</code></pre>
<p>You can also define an alias for the grid type, e.g.</p>
<pre><code>using grid_type = std::string [NROWS][NCOLS];
</code></pre>
<p>By the way, note how we use the namespace <code>std</code> to prefix the <code>string</code> type (in other words, <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1452721/whats-the-problem-with-using-namespace-std">don't use <code>using namespace std;</code></a>)</p>
<p>Then, you can define <code>moveToLocation</code> by providing an object of type <code>grid_type</code> and the coordinates. We have to provide the grid object by reference (i.e. with <code>&amp;</code>) since we want to modify it</p>
<pre><code>void moveToLocation (grid_type&amp; g, int x, int y) {

    std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\x1B[2J\x1B[H&quot;;  // clear the console

    for (int r=0; r&lt;NROWS; r++) {
        for (int c=0; c&lt;NCOLS; c++) {
            g[r][c] = &quot;o&quot;;
        }
    }
    g[x][y] = &quot;[]&quot;;

    for (int r=0; r&lt;NROWS; r++) {
        for (int c=0; c&lt;NCOLS; c++) {
            std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\t&quot; &lt;&lt; g[r][c];
        }
        std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Note how we use constants <code>NROWS</code> and <code>NCOLS</code> instead of hardcoded values.</p>
<p>Finally, you can go from top to bottom as follows with a for-loop</p>
<pre><code>int main()
{
    // We define a grid
    grid_type mygrid;

    // We set the initial column (in the middle).
    int c=NCOLS/2;

    // We iterate each row
    for (int r=0; r&lt;NROWS; r++) {
        moveToLocation (mygrid,r,c);
        std::this_thread::sleep_for(500ms);
        c += r%2==0 ? 1 : -1; // let the column change a little bit
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>(Note: there are likely many possible improvements beyond the mere scope of the question)</p>
<p><a href="https://godbolt.org/z/77zKnEhsY" rel="nofollow noreferrer">Demo</a></p>
